[5] Democratic Republic of the Congo: tecovirimat treatment trial
Date: October 2022
Source: The Lancet Infectious Diseases [edited]
https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(22)00604-1/fulltext


ref: Nakkazi E. Monkeypox trial to begin in DR Congo. Lancet Infect Dis. 2022; 22(10): 1425
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
As The Lancet Infectious Diseases went to press, the Democratic Republic of the Congo had plans to begin a large clinical trial of tecovirimat for the treatment of monkeypox. Tecovirimat first received regulatory approval for this indication, as well as for infections caused by other orthopoxviruses, from the European Medicines Agency in 2021, largely based on efficacy data from animal models. It was originally approved in 2018 for the treatment of smallpox.

DR Congo reported the 1st case of human monkeypox in 1970 and has had recurrent outbreaks since. In spite of this, "this will be the 1st clinical trial [of a monkeypox therapeutic] in Africa and only after the disease is a global problem", said Daniel Mukadi, the Regional Director of the National Institute of Biomedical Research in eastern DR Congo. "We are supportive of clinical trials being done here on the continent. The need for Africa to participate in the development of vaccines and therapeutics is one of our priorities. We encourage developers to come work with us in Africa", said Ahmed Ogwell Ouma, Acting Director of the Africa Centres for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).

DR Congo officials say they have completed training of staff who will implement the trial, but the remoteness of some of the sites and the ongoing pandemic will require special community engagement and communication strategies. "Communication and social mobilisation will be key tools to help us succeed with community engagement. We have to ensure that messages passed to the communities are correct and very clear", said Mukadi.

Although DR Congo has done many similar studies for different diseases, including Ebola, the environment for monkeypox is different in the same part of eastern DR Congo. For instance, one of the sites has active monkeypox cases in a very remote setting where the only source of power is solar, there is no infrastructure, and the virus has never been isolated before.

"It's a new challenge for us -- for example, we don't have the same setting as we did for Ebola. The platforms look different, but the context is still the same. We are in the eastern DRC in a remote area and we do have a background of COVID-19 ongoing and people know more about Ebola from the past 3 years in the same area", said Mukadi.

Between 1 Jan and 1 Sep 2022, 51â€ˆ163 laboratory-confirmed cases and 302 probable cases of monkeypox, including 17 deaths, had been reported to WHO from 102 Member States across all 6 WHO regions. Since May [2022], a high proportion of these cases have been reported from non-endemic countries. The WHO African Region reported 521 cases in the year up to 1 Sep 2022, including 195 in DR Congo and 220 in Nigeria. Case numbers could be higher but underreported. Researchers in Africa are trying to increase genomic surveillance in the region. Ifedayo Adetifa, Director-General of the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control, said that they are sequencing prospective samples and already catching up with historical cases.

DR Congo has a monkeypox programme with survivors, but it is poorly funded. "Monkeypox was of less interest for most people and not funded...it was thought to be African and only for Africans. Once we have cases out of Africa, so it becomes now a public health emergency, which is the same for Ebola", said Makadi.

But even as cases are rising, and the disease is ranked 3rd in Africa in terms of burden, Africa has no access to monkeypox therapeutics and vaccines. WHO has recommended that vaccines, once available, target only the most at-risk populations, including health workers. WHO officials say they are engaging with manufacturers and some of the countries that have access to them. "At this moment, we do not recommend mass vaccination, but targeted vaccination in the context of pre and post exposure prophylaxis for contacts", said Otim Patrick Ramadan, Health Emergency Officer at the WHO Regional Office for Africa. "We are also working with countries to prepare to develop the necessary regulatory approvals in the event that the vaccines become available so they can be used for the higher risk groups and contacts."

Monkeypox transmission in Africa still varies from elsewhere, mostly manifested at the household level, presenting a picture that has not changed much from what has been seen there before. WHO officials said they have not seen evidence or reports of transmission related to sexual activity in Africa. "Of course, we understand that in our region, the issue around sexuality is very sensitive and most times people will not be forthcoming", said Ramadan.

As the trial in DR Congo unfolds, a more coordinated monkeypox international response is expected, with further research into the disease and the ramping up of therapeutics, diagnostics, and vaccine production.

"We hope that manufacturers will agree to produce more therapeutics because of the world emergency. We have no idea about the costs for the therapeutics so far, but hopefully development partners will step in to purchase them and make them widely available", said Mukadi.

